div.div: when any of the following conditions is true, zero_byte shall present:
1. the nal_unit_type in the header of NAL unit is 7(sps) or 8(pps).
2. the byte stream NAL unit syntax structure contains the first NAL unit of an access unit in decoding order.

div.i: Note: During the decoding process, the nal_unit_type can only be known after the zero_byte has been identified. Hence the correctly method of identifying the presence of zero bytes is not by checking nal_unit_type, but
a. peek next 24 bits, if next_bits(24)!=0x0000001, the byte position pointed to by the bitstream pointer is a zero_byte syntax element, which shall be discarded, or
the byte stream NAL unit syntax structure contains the first NAL unit of an access unit in decoding order, there exists a zero_byte between leading_zero_8bits and start code prefix.

div.div: 1. RBSP could end in one or more cabac_zero_word (Rec. says this is to enable a NAL unit to have a size larger than that of the SODB under some circumstances. This is vague and it does not make sense.)

2. when the last byte of the RBSP is equal to 0x00 (which can only occur when the RBSP ends in cabac_zero_word), a final byte is appended to the end of the data, i.e., there could exist a byte of value 0x03 at the end of RBSP, this part has not been drawn in the figure above.
